          "body": "Verse 2 contains the psalm's only question, and it is a temporal cry of longing: *When will You come to me?* The question is situated between the king's aspiration ('I will give heed to the blameless way') and his first concrete resolution ('I will walk within my house with integrity'). Its placement reveals something important: the king's moral program is not self-sufficient virtue management. It is the preparation of a house worthy of Yahweh's presence. The king is building not a reputation but a dwelling place. Every exclusion of the deceitful, every suppression of the slanderer, every cultivation of the faithful is in service of this longing: that Yahweh would come and inhabit what the king has ordered. Peter Davids and others in the wisdom tradition read this verse in light of 2 Samuel 6 — the establishment of the ark in Jerusalem — but its force is not limited to a historical occasion. It is the perennial cry of any king or believer who longs for the manifest presence of God in the domestic sphere."
