          "title": "Inside-out governance — heart, house, city",
          "body": "The psalm's moral geography moves deliberately from the inside outward. The king begins with his own heart (101:2-4): he will walk with integrity of heart, refuse to set worthless things before his eyes, expel the perverse heart, and refuse acquaintance with evil. Then he moves to his household and circle (101:5-7): the slanderer is destroyed, the arrogant is not endured, the faithful are cultivated, the deceitful are expelled from the house. Finally he reaches the city (101:8): every morning he will cut off the wicked of the land from the city of Yahweh. The sequence is not accidental — it is the biblical order of authority and responsibility. A king who cannot govern his own heart cannot govern his household; a king who cannot govern his household will not govern his city rightly. Howard Hendricks captured this principle precisely: before you can lead others, you must lead yourself. Psalm 101 is the Old Testament royal statement of that principle."
