          "body": "Verses 5-7 form the psalm's most sustained section, and its organizing principle is binary: every characteristic either disqualifies or qualifies for proximity to the king. The excluded: the secret slanderer (101:5), the haughty of eye (101:5), the arrogant of heart (101:5), the practicer of deceit (101:7), the speaker of falsehood (101:7). The included: the faithful of the land (101:6), the one who walks in the blameless way (101:6). The criteria are not talent, wealth, or family — they are character. The king's court will be a community shaped by faithfulness and blamelessness, not by social advantage. What is striking is the emphasis on *covert* sins: secret slander (101:5) and deceit practiced as a habit (101:7) receive the same severity of response as overt wickedness. The psalm is not policing only the visible; it is demanding that the invisible dimensions of character — what is spoken in secret, what is harbored in the heart — meet the same standard as public conduct."
